and, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1480–1584":"circa 1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Overleden","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1480–1584":"1480–1584","about 1480":"circa 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"circa 1505","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1480–1584":"about 1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Deceased","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1480–1584":"1480–1584","about 1480":"about 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"about 1505","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Copper","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent and Surrey): occupational name either from Middle English <i>copere</i>, a variant of <i>cupere</i> ‘cooper, maker or seller of casks, buckets, and tubs’, found late as <i>copper</i>, or from Middle English <i>copper</i>, <i>cupper</i> ‘maker of cups and small vessels’ (Old Norse <i>koppari</i>).","English: in Sussex and perhaps the adjacent counties, probably also a variant of <b>Coppard</b>, either from a Middle English (from Old French, Middle Dutch, or both) personal name <i>Coppard</i> (an extended form of <i>Cop</i>, a pet form of <i>Jacob</i>), or perhaps from Middle English <i>cop(e)</i>, <i>coppe</i> ‘top, head’ + the pejorative suffix <i>-ard</i>, perhaps for someone with a large head.","Altered form of German   Kopper  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kopper","meanings":["German: from Middle Low German <i>kopper</i> ‘copper’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a copper dealer or coppersmith.","North German: occupational name, from Low German <i>Kopper</i> or <i>Köpper</i> ‘bloodletter’, i.e. someone who applied cups in order to effect a bleeding.","German: from a Germanized form of Slavic <i>kop(e)r</i> (from Old Slavic <i>koprъ</i>) ‘dill, fennel’ (compare   Koper   1), hence a topographic name or a metonymic occupational name for a herb grower or dealer."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":89,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"George Copper was born about 1480, in England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs George Cooper. He died in 1584, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 105."},"et":{"about 1480–1584":"umbes 1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Surnud","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1480–1584":"1480–1584","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"umbes 1505","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1480–1584":"noin 1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Kuollut","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1480–1584":"1480–1584","about 1480":"noin 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"noin 1505","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1480–1584":"environ 1480–1584","1485–Female":"1485–Décédée","1505–1584":"1505–1584","1480–1584":"1480–1584","about 1480":"environ 1480","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1505":"environ 1505","1584":"1584","1485":"1485","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Benchley, Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"George Copper est né environ 1480, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs George Cooper. Il est décédé en 1584, à Ke